<documentation>
  The Control4 Media Player V2 allows you to play videos stored on a Network Attached Storage (NAS) drive.

  This driver allows the Control4 system to control the Media Player V2 and allows the Control4 Navigator interface to be used to select a video title (requires Control4 1.7 or later system software).

  To configure the Media Player V2 in a system:

  1. Add the Media Player V2 (C4-MP2-E) driver to your project.

  2. Using Composer, add a Network File Storage driver to your system for the NAS drive which you use for video storage.  On the Properties page connect to the NAS drive by typing in the appropriate credentials then click Connect.

  3. Using Composer add a Network File Storage driver to your system for the network storage device which you use for video storage.  On the Properties page connect to the NAS drive by typing in the appropriate credentials and clicking on Connect.

  4. Use Composer, Media tab to scan the Network File Storage device for video content.  The Scan operation will identify video_ts format video files and ISO files that contain video_ts folders, add them to the media DB, and automatically associate the video meta data including cover art.

  5. For other video formats supported by the Media Player V2, you can use Composer to manually add these items to the media DB, use the Scan, Add Files Ending with function to retrieve the appropriate meta data from the web service, and enter the correct network path to the video file. If you have a video file format that is not listed in the drop down menu you can type in that file format extension (eg, .mp4).  They can then also be selected for playback using the Navigator interface.

  6.  A description of the available Properties settings available in the driver:
  Resolution:  Auto is the default setting; it allows the Media Player V2 and driver to negotiate the resolution over HDMI. Changing the setting will force the Media Player V2 to display a specific video resolution that the television supports.

  Current Resolution:  the resolution currently set on the Media Player V2. If the Resolution is set to Auto this will display the resolution negotiated over HDMI.

  Switchable Resolutions: At the time of video playback the user can change the video resolution of the Media Player V2 by using the page up and page down buttons on the Control4 System Remote Control. Video resolutions identified with true will be cycled through using the page up and page down buttons. Mark false any resolution that you do not want selectable from the remote.

  Background Image URL:  Allows the dealer to change the background image displayed on the Media Player V2 status screen.

  Screen Saver Image URL:  Allows the dealer to change the background image displayed on the Media Player V2 screen saver.

  Update URL:  indicates the stored location for the current Media Player V2 firmware.

  Auto Updates Enabled:  True  causes the Media Player V2 automatically update firmware when a new version is available.  Updates will only occur when the Control4 system software and/or Media Player V2 driver is upgraded.

  Switchable Resolutions:  The user can change the video Resolution of the Media Player V2 by using the page up and page down buttons on the Control4 System Remote Control.  Video resolutions identified with true will be cycled through using the page up and page down buttons.  Mark false any resolution that you do not want available to the television.

  Restart Playback on Reselect:  True causes the Media Player to start playback of selected movie from the beginning when the same movie is selected.  A setting of false mean the Media Player will not restart the same movie if reselected without first stopping the playing movie or selecting a different movie.  Note that setting this to false may resolve some issues with the movie restarting after an announcement is played in the room.

  7:  What video file formats does the Media Player V2 support?
  Because the file format (also known as the container) is only a part of the overall video file, it's difficult to say that any specific file format will always play.  A video file is made up of three main parts:
  1.  Encoded video (codec such as MPEG2, H.264, etc)
  2.  Encoded audio (AC3, AAC, etc)
  3.  File container (ifo/vob, avi, mp4, etc)
  For example, many of today's standard definition video files contain video that has been encoded using MPEG2, with an audio track encoded in Dolby Digital with both audio and video combined in a .vob file container.

  Many audio and video codecs are available from competing companies. For instance, Microsoft has developed the WMV and WMA file formats and associated codecs. A variety of software tools have also been developed to convert files into a broad range of video files. With the variety of audio and video codecs as well, as video file containers available from different companies, it is easy to understand that not all combinations of codecs and file formats will work together. For best results we recommend the following codec and file format combinations:

  Video Container     Vid Codec  Aud Codec  HDMI Aud   S/PIDF Stereo
  VIDEO TS(vob/ifo)   MPEG2	     AC3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  VIDEO TS(vob/ifo)   MPEG2	     DTS	      yes*	         yes*      no
  ISO	                MPEG2	     AC3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  ISO	                MPEG2	     DTS	      yes*	         yes*      no
  mp4	                H264	     AC3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  mp4	                FFmpeg	     AC3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  avi	                XviD	     mp3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  avi	                XviD	     AC3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  avi	                XviD	     mp3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  avi	                FFmpeg	     AC3	      yes	         yes	       yes
  avi	                FFmpeg	     mp3	      yes	         yes	       yes

  *Requires a receiver or TV that supports DTS.
</documentation>
